15 May 2014 18:48






Short and sweet is something we definitely don't have enough of these days, so it's an admirable thing to try for on occasion. The problem with that is that you need to make sure that what you're writing about is interesting enough to carry the article merely by the fact of its own existence.

In this case, this just doesn't cut it. All I'm really seeing is currents in the Great Pacific garbage patch that make patterns and group stuff together. If that's it, I'm underwhelmed. I'm also unsure why they automatically think that this phenomenon means . No possibility that something else is causing this? The mere existence of patterns doesn't really establish that this is a living sentient entity, in my view.

Also, you're working against the fact that the Great Pacific garbage patch is a horrifying phenomenon in real life that's mind-boggling to think about in terms of its scale and implications. Frankly,  pales in comparison to the real-world setting that you're working with.







